\subsection{Color: Cardelli Law or Intrinsic?}
Although $E(B-V)$ has traditionally been attributed to extinction, recent work by \citeauthor{conley08a} (\citeyear{conley08a}) has indicated that single parameter functions, such as dust laws, are in general unable to reproduce the variation in color seen in supernovae. They further find that the $U - B$ vs. $B - V$ relation found for their type Ia supernovae do not follow the relation one would expect for Milky-Way like dust.

% Conley fig
\begin{figure}[ht]
\begin{center}
\includegraphics[angle=0,scale=0.8]{./figures/conley/f10_color.eps}
\end{center}
\caption{
The derived $U - B$ vs. $B - V$ relation found by \citeauthor{conley08a} (\citeyear{conley08a}). The best fit to the sample is the solid line. The arrow is the relation one would expect from Milky-Way like dust ($R_{v} = [1.6,3.1,4.6]$).
}
\label{fig:conleyfigure}
\end{figure}
\clearpage

In line with the results of \citeauthor{conley08a} our first eigenvector suggests that color is partially an intrinsic quantity, and not simply due to extinction. If color is purely an extinction related effect we would expect this eigenvector to be nearly featureless so that line ratios would be completely uncorrelated with color. However, we observe deviations from our first eigenvector that align with the MgII feature, the FeIII features and the SiII features. This suggests that color is, to some extent, correlated with spectral features and is therefore not entirely extinction but is intrinsic to each individual supernova. 

If the color excess observed in type Ia spectra was purely due to extinction then we should be able to use the Cardelli law \citep{cardelli89a} to account for it. We therefore attempt to warp the Hsiao template \citep{hsiao07a}, a template created by taking the average spectra near max of over 100 type Ia supernovae, with the Cardelli law. We fix $ R_{v} =3.1$ and vary $A_{v}$ until we find a minimum in the $\chi^{2}$ overlap between the warped Hsiao spectrum and our observed spectra.

While many of our spectra appear to be able to be fit by a simple Cardelli law applied to the Hsiao template, nine supernova fail. As expected the peculiar SN1991T and SN1991bg are not well fit. SN1998de, SN1998bp, SN1999cl, SN2000dk, and SN2000cx have spectral features that can not be matched with only a Cardelli law. SN1998aq and SN1999aa seem to fit well at first glance, but both have nonphysical preferred values of $A_{V}$, $-0.031$ for SN1998aq and $-0.062$ for SN1999aa. Cardelli dust can not make a supernova bluer, and so we are forced to conclude that their color is not dust related. 

