We plot the normalized weight functions of our supernova against each other. Supernova with similar features will cluster. Further, it is possible to calculate a extinction vector in this space which allows us to observe exactly how much color excess is due to extinction. We plot the extinction vector by using the Cardelli law to warp the average spectrum from our PCA. We fix $R_{V} = 3.1$ and increment $A_{V}$ by 0.2. We then normalize this spectrum by its area again and subtract off the average spectrum. We then dot this with an eigenvector which gives us a weight. Mathematically this is:

$$ c_{j}^{CCM} = \vec{\xi_{j}} \cdot \left[ \frac {\vec{\mu} \cdot CCM(R_{V}=3.1,A_{V})}{Normalize} - \vec{\mu} \right] $$

Where $\vec{\mu}$ is our average spectra, $CCM(R_{V}=3.1,A_{V})$ is the Cardelli factor, and $\vec{\xi_{j}}$ is our $j$th eigenvector.

